data.content:
Here's the complete migration with explanations of every pitfall:

## Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Response.End()`** — doesn't exist in ASP.NET Core. It threw `ThreadAbortException` in Framework to forcibly halt the pipeline. Core uses a pipeline model where you simply return a result.

2. **`Response.Redirect(url, true)`** — the `endResponse` parameter is gone. In Framework, `true` called `Thread.Abort()` internally. Core's redirect is just setting headers — no thread aborting.

3. **`ThreadAbortException`** — **cannot occur** in .NET Core/.NET 5+. `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Any `catch (ThreadAbortException)` block is dead code.

4. **`Response.Write()`** — replaced by returning `IActionResult` types or writing to `Response.Body` stream.

5. **WebForms event model** (`btnExport_Click`) — doesn't exist. Use MVC action methods with `[HttpPost]`.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Return a FileResult — no need to manually set headers or call Response.End()
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        // Use the [Authorize] attribute instead of manual checks,
        // or check inline — but never rely on ThreadAbortException.
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
            // In Core, Redirect() just returns a 302 result.
            // No thread abort, no exception — execution continues
            // past this point only if you forget `return`.
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) — it cannot happen in .NET 8.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Forgetting `return`** | `Redirect()` returns an object — it doesn't halt execution. Code after it **will run** unless you `return`. |
| **Dead exception handlers** | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` compiles but never triggers. Remove it or you'll mask logic errors. |
| **Writing to Response directly** | If you write to `Response.Body` *and* return an `IActionResult`, you get `InvalidOperationException` ("response already started"). Pick one. |
| **`Response.End()` replacement** | There is none. If you're in middleware and need to short-circuit, call `return` — don't look for an equivalent. |
| **Auth checks** | Replace manual `IsAuthenticated` checks with `[Authorize]` attribute + authentication middleware in `Program.cs`. |

## Program.cs Setup (required)

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* configure scheme */);
builder.Services.AddAuthorization();

var app = builder.Build();

app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();
app.MapControllers();
app.Run();
```

**Bottom line:** ASP.NET Core has no thread-aborting flow control. Every action returns a result object (`IActionResult`). Remove all `Response.End/Clear/Write` patterns and all `ThreadAbortException` handling — they are relics of the WebForms pipeline.
